## Critical: Edit Buffers, Not Files

When collaborating with pi on a file, pi MUST edit the Emacs buffer directly rather than modifying the file on disk. 

If pi edits the file on disk while the user has it open in Emacs, we risk:
- Overwriting each other's changes
- Confusing "file modified on disk" prompts
- Out-of-sync state between buffer and file

Commands needed:
- Replace buffer content (whole buffer or regions)
- Insert text at point or specific positions
- Apply diffs/patches to buffer content

The buffer-editing approach keeps everything synchronized and allows immediate visual feedback in the editor.
